title: For Sale:  Daisy Heddon VL Caseless  .22
postcontent: Offering a used Daisy Heddon VL Rifle, 18" barrel. Overall a nice collector piece from 1968-1969. The history of the Daisy is as follows: In 1961 Case Hough, the president of Daisy Heddon division of Victor Comptometer, purchased the design of a new firearm system. The new system was developed by a Belgian Chemist named Jules Van Langenhover. The new gun would be known as the Daisy V/L rifle.[1] The V/L ammunition consisted of a .22 caliber bullet with a small cylinder of propellant on the back, and no primer.[2] The rifle resembled a typical spring-air rifle, but the 2000° hot, high pressure air served not only to propel the projectile but also to ignite the propellant on the back of the V/L cartridge. The rifle uses a small, unique and well designed part called an Obturator (obturator/ignitor) to compress the air as it is pushed through a tiny hole. This air is heated as it is pushed through the small hole enough to ignite the powder of the caseless round.[3] The V/L guns and ammunition were discontinued in 1969 after the US Bureau of Alcohol, Tobacco, Firearms and Explosives ruled that they constituted a firearm, and Daisy, which was not licensed to manufacture firearms, decided to discontinue manufacture rather than become a firearms manufacturer. About 23,000 of the rifles were made before production ceased. FTF in Graham NC 325.00 or buyer pays shipping.

title: For Sale:  Vintage Smith and Wesson Model 39-2 9mm Pistol with 6 Magazines
postcontent: For sale we have a highly collectible Smith and Wesson Model 39-2 semiautomatic pistol. As you may know, the Model 39 has a place in firearms history as the first modern American-made 9mm service pistol to be adopted by a major police agency, signalling the beginning of the end of the revolver era in policing. This particular pistol was made in 1974-75 and is in excellent condition, just as serviceable today as a defense pistol as it is desireable as a collectible, a must for any serious Smith and Wesson enthusiast. The Model 39-2 is famous for its incredibly comfortable grip angle and shape.This pistol comes with its two original 8-round blued magazines, which are very hard to find. In addition, included are four brand new 9 round magazines so that you can shoot your pistol as much as you like. This pistol may be seen by appointment only at my office just outside of Homestead. I will listen to best offers, and suggestions for trades on this firearm, but please be reasonable. Cash always speaks loudest. title: For Sale:  Classic Ruger Speed-Six .357 Revolver with Extras
postcontent:
For sale we have a nice older classic Ruger revolver from the late 1970s. It is the Speed-Six model .357 Magnum with round butt grip frame and a 2.75 inch barrel. This is a blue finish revolver with a very smooth action, and is quite accurate. Ruger discontinued this model in 1988 shortly after the GP-100 revolver was introduced. It provided serious competition to the Smith and Wesson revolvers of the day, and fits in most holsters made for Smith and Wesson K-frame revolvers. This model was issued to U.S. Customs Agents as well as the Postal Inspectors back in the day, as well as to agents of the Naval Investigative Service, which later became N.C.I.S.
The gun wears a pair of Herrett's wood grips, but also comes with three other sets of rubber grips of different styles, so I'm sure you can find something you like. It also comes with two new Safariland speed loaders as well.This revolver may be seen by appointment only at my office just outside of Homestead. title: For Sale/Trade:  Sphinx SDP Alpha and Sig P239 SAS Gen 2 in 9mm
postcontent:
Trade pending, thanks for your interest.
 
 
I have two excellent quality handguns on offer for sale or trade, individually or two-for-one.First is a Sphinx SDP Alpha Compact in 9mm, made in Switzerland and imported by Kriss USA. If you know Swiss firearms like the Schmidt-Rubin K31, you know the Swiss reputation for craftsmanship doesn't stop with their watches.  The gun resembles a CZ P-07 with the internals of a CZ-75B, but most of the receiver is of alloy construction. I purchased this new back in the summer. I am very impressed with the workmanship and the function of the gun, but the sights are just a little too "European" for me. I like a six-o'clock hold, and I'm not willing to carve up an expensive gun like this just to change the point of aim.  It is, without question, the softest-shooting 9mm I've ever handled. Sphinx is known for high-end competition pistols costing several thousand dollars, so the soft recoil, negligible muzzle rise, and clean-breaking trigger in this production model are undoubtedly owed to the company's competition heritage.  Included with the gun are two 15-round magazines, a full cleaning kit, magazine loader, and three interchangeable backstraps. I'm offering the Sphinx alone for $700.Second is a Sig Sauer P239 SAS Gen 2.  The SAS designation stands for "Sig Anti-Snag", which simply means that some of the harder angles were rounded off at the Sig custom shop to prevent the gun from catching on clothing when carrying concealed. This model includes the short-reset trigger (SRT) and Siglites factory night sights.  This has been my carry gun for a couple of years now, and it's the 2nd one I've owned. I was initially drawn to the P239 for its size, all-metal composition, and the elongated trigger guard which is more accommodating to larger hands or gloves. This gun also comes with two 8-round magazines, the factory case, and a cheap rubber Hogue finger groove grip. I have an Alien Gear IWB holster for it if you'd like, all for $600 out the door. I have additional factory 10-round magazines available for $30 each. I'm cool with trades, as I have listed below. I'm getting a little too heavy on handguns, and there isn't a whole lot that I haven't owned at some point or another. I'm not looking for non-firearm items, and I'm not looking to give these guns away. Bud's sells these two for $1,848 together, so here's a chance to get a couple of reputable guns for reasonable prices.  I've been working a lot lately, but I usually have one day off per week. I'll do my best to work with my buyers' schedules. I travel to the Shelby/Mansfield/Ashland area occasionally on weekends off to visit family; I'd be happy to bring them along if you live between there and Columbus, but time doesn't often permit me to travel too far out of town otherwise. Buyers must be over the age of 21 and show a valid Ohio ID.  Thanks for looking!
